Rating: 4
I made this exactly as written the first time for my daughter's preschool graduation (except I substituted toasted pecans for the walnuts and tripled the quantity of everything) and it was delicious, although I felt that, with a few tweaks, it could be even better. So it was that, the second time around, instead of shallots, which were overpowering even though very finely chopped, I used the same amount of red onions marinated in honey, vinegar, and a small amount of olive oil. Do this step before you begin all other chopping and mixing and that will be sufficient marinating time. Rather than 2 cups of red grapes, which were too numerous and too sweet, I used one cup of cored but unpeeled, thinly sliced and chopped, Granny Smith apple. These two changes improved the taste tremendously! Other changes that did not make much difference either way: used leftover roast turkey, which is as good as chicken but perhaps soaks up more moisture. Did not have celery on hand and did not miss it. Used dried tarragon instead of fresh--fresh is better but dried is fine. Increased the black pepper and ground it myself. Toasted walnuts or toasted pecans-- either way tasty. It was more moist the first day, and the various flavors stood out independently. By the third day, the walnuts are still crunchy and the apples are less distinctive but it is still delicious!! The best chicken salad I've ever made.

